  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Considering HLSL Rendering**\n\nOkay, I\'m now wrestling with the core challenge: translating HLSL code for in-browser rendering. The ShaderToy inspiration is clear, but the language difference necessitates a clever bridge. My focus is on the feasibility of achieving real-time, interactive HLSL visualization within a web environment. The \"how\" is proving to be the crux of this.\n\n\n**Exploring HLSL Translation**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on the best HLSL-to-browser rendering path. I\'ve realized the core issue: the language gap between HLSL and WebGL/WebGPU. My thinking is leaning towards either a direct transpiler from HLSL to GLSL. Considering a real-time shader renderer that automatically handles syntax differences between HLSL and GLSL sounds promising, too. I\'m focusing on the elegant simplicity of the translation.\n\n\n**Mapping HLSL to GLSL**\n\nI\'m making progress identifying the key differences between HLSL fragment shader features and their GLSL equivalents. I\'m focusing on a robust transpiler, and WebGL 2 (GLSL ES 3.00) seems like the most stable target for now, considering browser compatibility. I\'ve begun mapping common types and intrinsics, like `lerp` to `mix` and `mul` to matrix multiplication operators. The details of matrix multiplication order are also becoming clearer.\n\n\n**Translating HLSL Functions**\n\nI\'m now deep-diving into the function translation specifics. I\'m focusing on those specific HLSL function calls and determining the appropriate GLSL equivalents. The mapping I\'ve identified is fairly straightforward, such as `atan2` to `atan`, and `saturate` to `clamp`. The trickier parts involve handling the slightly different behavior of `fmod` in GLSL, where I may have to consider a custom implementation. I\'m also ensuring that the translation handles `clip` properly. I\'ve focused my attention on the shader entry points now.\n\n\n**Defining HLSL Template**\n\nI\'m now concretely defining a ShaderToy-like HLSL template. My goal is to use this as a starting point. Now, I\'m thinking about making a JS compiler/transpiler that can transform this HLSL code to GLSL ES 3.00, and run it on WebGL 2. The idea of an editor with syntax highlighting and error reporting for HLSL is really exciting. I\'m focusing on features such as preset shaders, time control, mouse input, and custom textures.\n\n\n**Prioritizing User Content**\n\nI\'m now determining how to handle user-authored shader content. While not explicitly requested, the similarity to Shadertoy makes local storage with an import/export option essential. I\'m also considering Firebase integration for cloud saving, which aligns with the \"user-created content\" guideline. A gorgeous client-side app with stellar local storage seems like a good approach. Let\'s start there.\n\n\n**Implementing Editor Features**\n\nI\'m now fully immersed in the editor implementation. I\'m focusing on incorporating a code editor with HLSL syntax highlighting. I\'m excited by the possibilities of `@monaco-editor/react`, which offers a VS Code-like experience. I\'m prioritizing user-friendliness by designing rich presets, complete controls, rendering stats, and error logs with inline highlights, while also making sure preset texture slots are included.\n\n\n**Refining Core Functionality**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on the core functionality, as the strict \"user intent\" directive has become clear. My main focus is a barebones, real-time HLSL rendering environment akin to ShaderToy. The editor, rendering, controls, and error logging are all high-priority features. The hard rule is: no AI, cloud, or unsolicited features. The goal is to avoid feature creep.\n\n\n"
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 13
      nanos: 190663296
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
