  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Analyzing Transpilation**\n\nI\'m now diving into the design of the HLSL to GLSL ES 3.00 transpiler. I\'ve begun analyzing the key differences between the two languages, focusing initially on data types like `float` which has a direct equivalent. The goal is to identify HLSL\'s unique features to ensure accurate translation.\n\n\n**Mapping Data Types**\n\nI\'ve made significant progress with data type mapping. Direct equivalents like `float` to `float` and vector/matrix types now have robust translations (e.g., `float2x2` to `mat2`). I\'ve also addressed the `double` issue by substituting it with `float`. Moreover, the crucial insight regarding constructors has been validated: replacing the keywords works for constructors as well! This leads to the direct keyword replacement for declarations like `float4 color = ...` into `vec4 color = ...` via regex.\n\n\n**Refining Translation Rules**\n\nI\'m now refining the translation rules, realizing that simple string replacement for data types is insufficient. I\'m focusing on incorporating word boundaries into the regex patterns to prevent unintended transformations (e.g., `float2ing`). I have finalized the data type replacements including `float`, `int`, `bool`, and matrix types. Moreover, I\'m working through intrinsics replacements, and a function for `saturate` as a robust replacement. This will avoid regex complexities and ensure accuracy across data types.\n\n\n**Defining Intrinsic Overloads**\n\nI\'m now focusing on handling HLSL intrinsics. I\'m building overload functions in GLSL for common functions like `saturate` and `lerp`, which aren\'t native in GLSL or behave differently. This will ensure consistent behavior. I\'ve defined `saturate` to use `clamp`, and `lerp` to use `mix`. The goal is to provide type-safe GLSL equivalents, encompassing scalar and vector variations.\n\n\n**Implementing Intrinsic Equivalents**\n\nI\'m now implementing the GLSL equivalents for HLSL intrinsics. I have addressed `frac`, defining overloaded functions for scalar and vector types using `fract`. I\'ve also carefully defined `fmod` to ensure it mirrors HLSL\'s behavior, leveraging `trunc` which is supported in GLSL ES 3.00. This should ensure consistent results. Next up is `mul`.\n\n\n**Defining `mul` Overloads**\n\nI\'ve made a crucial breakthrough! I\'ve realized `mul` is a matrix multiplication helper in HLSL, so I\'m defining GLSL overloads to handle matrix-vector and matrix-matrix operations, eliminating the need for regex. I have implemented a clean approach: defining the `mul` functions directly, covering `vec2`, `vec3`, and `vec4` for matrix-vector and matrix-matrix types. Also, `atan2` is simply `atan`.\n\n\n\n**Defining Derivative Functions**\n\nI\'m now defining equivalents for HLSL\'s derivative functions. I\'ve successfully translated `ddx` and `ddy` using `dFdx` and `dFdy` in GLSL, implementing overloaded functions for various data types (float, vec2, vec3, vec4). Next, I\'m defining `rsqrt` using `inversesqrt`. Also, `rcp` is defined as a simple division.\n\n\n**Defining `clip` and `mad`**\n\nI\'m now focusing on `clip` and `mad`. I\'ve realized that in HLSL, `clip(x)` discards the pixel if `x < 0`. I have defined overloads for `clip` for scalar and vector types using `discard` in GLSL: this is now working! Next up, `mad` is just an `fma` in GLSL, so that\'s easy!\n\n\n**Confirming WebGL2 Compatibility**\n\nI\'ve just ensured that using `fma` is not universally safe for GLSL ES 3.00, so I\'ve replaced it with a multiplication and addition for safety and compatibility. I have also implemented texture sampling using the `texture()` function, and aliased the `tex2D` to `texture()`.\n\n\n**Translating Texture Sampling**\n\nI\'m now focusing on texture sampling and discovered a simple regex translation for DX11 style: `(\\w+)\\.Sample\\s*\\(\\s*\\w+\\s*,\\s*([^)]+)\\)` -> `texture($1, $2)`, which elegantly handles cases like `iChannel0.Sample(iSampler0, uv)`. I\'ve also implemented  `(\\w+)\\.SampleLevel\\s*\\(\\s*\\w+\\s*,\\s*([^,]+)\\s*,\\s*([^)]+)\\)` -> `textureLod($1, $2, $3)` for level of detail sampling. Now, I\'m thinking about the entry point structure and how to support both Shadertoy\'s HLSL and a return-style as well.\n\n\n**Defining Entry Point**\n\nI\'m now focusing on handling HLSL entry points within the GLSL `main` function. I\'ve designed a system to detect different entry point signatures such as `mainImage(out float4 ..., in float2 ...)` or `float4 mainImage(float2 ...)` and transpile them to the correct GLSL `main` function calls. This will allow compatibility with Shadertoy-style HLSL code.\n\n\n**Detecting Entry Signatures**\n\nI\'m now writing code to auto-detect and transpile different HLSL entry point signatures into GLSL. I\'m focusing on handling both `mainImage(out float4, in float2)` and `float4 mainImage(float2)` signatures, ensuring they map correctly to the GLSL `main` function. This approach ensures compatibility with Shadertoy-style code and various user-defined structures. I\'ve designed a robust system to parse and transpile various user-defined structures.\n\n\n**Implementing Uniform Declarations**\n\nI\'m now implementing the translation of common Shadertoy uniform variables. Renaming the user\'s `main` to `userMain` avoids conflicts. We should declare the uniforms as they are in WebGL2, so I\'m handling `iResolution`, `iTime`, `iTimeDelta`, `iFrame`, and `iMouse`. I\'m declaring `iChannel0` as `sampler2D` in the GLSL output.\n\n\n**Structuring the Application**\n\nI\'m now focusing on application structure, aiming for a multi-module design to maintain clarity. I\'ve defined `src/types.ts` for data types, `src/utils/transpiler.ts` for the HLSL transpiler, `src/components/ShaderCanvas.tsx` for the WebGL rendering canvas, `src/components/ShaderEditor.tsx` for the code editor, `src/components/ShaderPresets.tsx` for shader templates, and `src/components/TextureSelector.tsx` for texture management.\n\n\n**Generating Preset Textures**\n\nI\'m now generating procedural textures for `iChannel0` through `iChannel3`. The app will build noise, checkerboard, sine wave, and organic textures on startup, and use them as WebGL textures. This offline-first approach eliminates external dependencies and ensures high-fidelity. I\'ll define a `ShaderPreset` type to organize the templates. I\'ll start with `src/types.ts`.\n\n\n"
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 26
      nanos: 985090226
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
