  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Designing the Transpiler**\n\nI\'m now focused on building `src/utils/transpiler.ts`, the heart of the HLSL-to-GLSL transpilation process. I\'m aiming for a robust design, specifically targeting a GLSL 3.00 es fragment shader. I\'m currently thinking through the fundamental translation steps and envisioning the basic structure of the resulting GLSL code.\n\n\n**Defining the GLSL Template**\n\nI\'ve finalized the GLSL 3.00 es fragment shader template, establishing the base structure for the transpiled output. This foundational structure includes precision definitions, input variables (uv coordinates), uniforms (resolution, time, mouse, textures), and the essential output `fragColor`. I also defined HLSL compatibility helpers like type aliases and legacy macros, ensuring smooth translation from HLSL.\n\n\n**Implementing HLSL Compatibility Functions**\n\nI\'ve just added several HLSL compatibility functions to the transpiler. I\'ve focused on essential mathematical operations. Specifically, I\'ve implemented `saturate`, `lerp`, `frac`, and `fmod` to ensure smooth translation from HLSL. I now have the implementation for float and vec2, vec3, and vec4 data types for those functions.\n\n\n**Expanding Matrix & Math Functions**\n\nI\'ve just finished adding crucial matrix multiplication functions, ensuring compatibility for various vector and matrix types. I\'ve also integrated `atan2`, as well as `ddx`, `ddy`, and `rsqrt` implementations, to align with the HLSL standard. Now I am working on the remaining functions.\n\n\n**Adding Remaining Functions**\n\nI\'ve just added several more functions to complete the HLSL compatibility layer. I\'ve included `rsqrt`, `rcp`, `clip`, and `mad`, with support for multiple vector and float types. I\'m now contemplating the user code integration. My next steps involve replacing HLSL type names with their GLSL equivalents through defined aliases.\n\n\n**Refining Type Name Replacement**\n\nI realized type name replacement via `#define` is simpler than I initially thought! Casting and constructors like `float4(1, 2, 3, 4)` translate seamlessly to `vec4(1, 2, 3, 4)`. I\'ve just identified HLSL semantics like `: SV_Target` that require stripping with a regex.\n\n\n**Refining Semantic Stripping**\n\nI\'ve just refined the semantic stripping process. I initially considered a simple regex, but I realized it could interfere with ternary operators. I\'ve now crafted two targeted regex expressions to address HLSL semantics, ensuring precise removal. The first handles parameter semantics, and the second addresses return value semantics, completely and specifically removing the HLSL semantics tags.\n\n\n**Translating Sampling Syntax**\n\nI\'m now implementing the texture sampling translation. I\'ve formulated regex patterns to convert HLSL\'s `Sample` and `SampleLevel` calls into GLSL\'s `texture` and `textureLod` functions. I\'m confident in the translation logic; it seems solid. Now, I\'m turning my attention towards entry point translation. I need to handle common variations of the `mainImage` function, and ensure the type replacements.\n\n\n**Refining Type Replacements**\n\nI\'ve decided on a direct source code replacement for data types, rather than `#define` macros. I\'m focusing now on updating the transpiler\'s regex patterns. I am implementing a comprehensive search-and-replace system for HLSL type keywords with their GLSL equivalents. I will replace all basic data types as well as matrix types. I am also checking how to integrate textures. I want to keep the process clean and avoid any potential compiler confusion.\n\n\n**Handling Texture Declarations**\n\nI\'m now focusing on handling texture and sampler declarations in the HLSL code. I\'ll map `Texture2D` to `sampler2D` in the GLSL output. Since the uniform samplers like `iChannel0` are already declared in the GLSL header, I need to comment out any redeclarations in the user\'s HLSL code to prevent conflicts. I\'ve crafted a regex to identify and comment out these redeclarations, ensuring a clean GLSL output.\n\n\n**Preventing Redeclarations**\n\nI\'ve just focused on preventing redeclaration errors for uniforms like `iResolution`, `iTime`, and others, since those are already declared in the header. I\'ve created several regex patterns to comment out these declarations in the user\'s HLSL code, improving robustness. I\'m now developing the entry point mapping to translate various `mainImage` signatures to the GLSL `main` function, to cover cases where users use `void mainImage( out vec4 fragColor, in vec2 fragCoord )` and `vec4 mainImage( vec2 fragCoord )`.\n\n\n**Mapping Entry Points**\n\nI\'m now focused on handling different `mainImage` function signatures. I am creating regex patterns to transform them into the standard GLSL `main` function. I\'ve designed logic to rename conflicting `main` functions to `userMain`, covering cases like `vec4 main(vec2 fragCoord)` and ensuring proper integration with `fragColor`. I\'m working to remove any semantics associated to the original `main`, before transforming the function.\n\n\n**Mapping Legacy Entry Points**\n\nI\'m now dealing with legacy HLSL shaders and the variety of entry point definitions. I\'ve realized that I need to handle cases where users might be returning a float4 from `main()`, which translates to the GLSL `fragColor` assignment. Specifically, I\'m generating a `main` function to assign to the declared `fragColor` output variable. Now I am handling situations with no entry point, providing a fallback or error, ensuring robustness in the face of diverse HLSL code styles.\n\n\n**Calculating Line Offset**\n\nI\'m now fully focused on calculating the line offset, critical for mapping GLSL compiler errors back to the user\'s HLSL code. I\'ll determine how many lines are in the generated GLSL header before the user\'s code is injected. This is essential for providing accurate error reporting in Monaco Editor, enabling debugging. The goal is to accurately pinpoint the HLSL line causing the failure, even with concatenated GLSL code.\n\n\n"
