    thinking: "**Assembling Key Components**\n\nI\'m incredibly excited, we have all the modular pieces in place! We\'ve got `src/types.ts`, the transpiler in `src/utils/transpiler.ts`, presets in `src/utils/presets.ts`, and texture generation in `src/utils/textureGenerator.ts`. Components are covered by `src/components/ShaderCanvas.tsx` and `src/components/ShaderEditor.tsx` and now `src/components`. This feels like the pivotal moment!\n\n\n**Integrating App Components**\n\nI\'m now focusing on `src/App.tsx`! I\'m planning out the state management and layout, outlining state variables for presets, HLSL code, texture channels, and compile errors. I\'m prioritizing a clean, professional UI with a header for the title and state, and a quick info bar to display important render stats. My goal is a cohesive, high-quality dashboard.\n\n\n**Refining The Layout**\n\nI\'m optimizing the app\'s grid layout, specifically for larger screens. I\'ve decided on the classic ShaderToy setup: the code editor takes up 7 columns, and the viewport/controls 5. Below that, I\'ll stack the Texture channel manager and presets selector. My next step is a simple interactive Quick-Reference cheat sheet for HLSL developers. I\'m excited by how accessible and convenient this will be!\n\n\n"
